04848nam a22007815i 9780823273690DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232736907 a10.1515/97808232736902doi  a(DE-B1597)555199  a(OCoLC)956320886  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB3279.H49C654513 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a1931 aDerrida, Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeidegger, Philosophy, and Politics :bThe Heidelberg Conference /cPhilippe Lacoue-Labarthe, Hans-Georg Gadamer, Jacques Derrida; Mireille Calle-Gruber. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (116 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tEvent of the archive -- tConference of February 5, 1988 -- tMeeting of February 6, 1988 -- tAppendix: "like Plato in Syracuse" -- tNotes 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn February 1988, philosophers Jacques Derrida, Hans-Georg Gadamer, and Philippe Lacoue-Labarthe came together in Heidelberg before a large audience to discuss the philosophical and political implications of Martin Heidegger's thought. This event took place in the very amphitheater in which, more than fifty years earlier, Heidegger, as rector of the University of Freiburg and a member of the Nazi Party, had given a speech entitled "The University in the New Reich." Heidegger's involvement in Nazism has always been, and will remain, an indelible scandal, but what is its real relation to his work and thought? And what are the responsibilities of those who read this work, who analyze and elaborate this thought? Conversely, what is at stake in the wholesale dismissal of this important but compromised twentieth-century philosopher?In 1988, in the wake of the recent publication of Victor Farias's Heidegger and Nazism, and of the heated debates that ensued, these questions had become more pressing than ever. The reflections presented by three of the most prominent of Heidegger's readers, improvised in French and transcribed here, were an attempt to approach these questions before a broad public, but with a depth of knowledge and a complex sense of the questions at issue that have been often lacking in the press. Ranging over two days and including exchanges with one another and with the audience, the discussions pursued by these major thinkers remain highly relevant today, especially following the publication of Heidegger's already notorious "Black Notebooks," which have added another chapter to the ongoing debates over this contested figure. The present volume recalls a highly charged moment in this history, while also drawing the debate toward its most essential questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aDerrida. 4aFrench philosophy. 4aGadamer. 4aHeidegger and nazism. 4aHeidegger. 4aLacoue-Labarthe. 4aphilosophy and politics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aCalle-Gruber, Mireille, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFort, Jeff1 aGadamer, Hans-Georg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLacoue-Labarthe, Philippe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNancy, Jean-Luc08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327369040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823273690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823273690.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA